\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 From left to right, these signatures are:  1. one flat;  2. three sharps;  3. three flats cancelled; 4. two flats cancelled;  5. one flat doubled at the octave in old book notation;  6. two sharps, one of which is doubled at the octave in old book notation;  7. two flats both doubled at the octave (note that ledger lines appear automatically);  8. molle in chant notation;  9. and 10. unconventional signatures.  In particular, Example 10  is a valid way to describe a modal scale combining a raised 4th (Lydian) with a lowered 7th (Mixolydian) both commencing on C.\par
